    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-06-21T18:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-06-21T18:40:00-05:00" n="304"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d304">
                <head>304. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant (<persName type="from"
                        >Rostow</persName>) to President <persName type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d304fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Country File, Jordan, Vol. II. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-06-21T19:40:00-04:00">June 21, 1966, 7:40 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have checked with Secretary <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>,
                    as you requested, on the economic program loan for Jordan. I have just received
                    word from <pb facs="0638" n="606" xml:id="pg_606"/> him that he concurs in the
                    recommendation of Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>, David
                    Bell, <persName corresp="#p_SCL1">Charles Schultze</persName>, and myself.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d304fn2">
                        <persName>Rostow</persName>’s June 17 memorandum to <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> requesting his views, a June 21
                        message telling <persName>Rostow</persName>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> had called to give his
                        concurrence, and a memorandum of June 27 from <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                            >McNamara</persName> to <persName>Rostow</persName> giving his formal
                        concurrence are ibid.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In relation to this loan, you will be interested in a talk I had this morning
                    with <persName corresp="#p_PS9">Shimon Peres</persName>, former Israeli Defense
                    Minister, whom Abe Feinberg brought in. He spoke with great respect of <persName
                        corresp="#p_HIT1">Hussein</persName> and cited the unspoken “agreement”
                    between Israel and Jordan to dampen border troubles. He made clear that Israel
                    prizes <persName corresp="#p_HIT1">Hussein</persName>’s independence of Cairo to
                    which our aid to Jordan is decisive.</p>
                <p>I recommend you approve this loan.<note n="3" xml:id="d304fn3">The approval line
                        is checked.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
